    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "To wrap this up, let's look at a real-world diagnostic scenario. When troubleshooting a faulty circuit, you often have to switch between measuring active flow and the physical properties of the components. Using the wrong tool or using it at the wrong time doesn't just give you bad data—it can destroy your equipment."
    ],
    "questionText": "You are investigating a motor that is overheating. You first need to measure the rate of electrical flow while the motor is running, and then you need to check the opposition to flow within the motor's internal windings. Identify the two specific instruments required for these tasks and explain why the circuit's power state must be changed before using the second instrument.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Identify the Ammeter for measuring the rate of flow (current).",
      "Identify the Ohmmeter for measuring the opposition to flow (resistance).",
      "Explain that the Ammeter is used while the circuit is live/running.",
      "Explain that the circuit must be isolated (made dead) before using the Ohmmeter.",
      "State that using an Ohmmeter on a live circuit will damage the instrument or provide false readings because the meter uses its own internal battery."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about which meter measures 'flow' and which measures 'opposition,' and remember the golden rule about using an Ohmmeter on energized equipment."
  }
